{{Infobox language |name = Isaurian |region = [[Isauria]] |states = Asia Minor |era = until the 5th century AD |familycolor = unclassified |family= [[Unclassified language|unclassified]]; personal names appear to be [[Luwian]] |script = |iso3 = none |glotto=none }}
'''Isaurian''' is an [[extinct language]] spoken in the area of [[Isaura]], [[Asia Minor]]. The personal names of its users appear to be derived from [[Luwian]] and thus [[Indo-European language|Indo-European]].<ref>Frank R. Trombley and John W. Watt, ''The Chronicle of Pseudo-Joshua the Stylite'' (Liverpool University Press, 2000), p. 12; Linda Honey, "Justifiably Outraged or Simply Outrageous? The Isaurian Incident of Ammianus Marcellinus 14.2," in ''Violence in Late Antiquity: Perceptions and Practices'' (Ashgate, 2006), 50.</ref> Epigraphic evidence, including funerary inscriptions, is found into the 5th century AD.<ref>Honey, "The Isaurian incident," p. 50.</ref>
